Our runtime is dependent on both values of $n$ and $m$. The runtime of $\text {MultiplyPoly}(a, b)$ is $O(\degree (a)+\degree (b))$. Each polynomial in $P$ has degree $m$. In the start, $poly$ has degree $m$ and so the first iteration of MultiplyPoly has runtime $m + m = 2m$. The next iteration has runtime $2m + m = 3m$. Continuing in this manner, we see that the $i$th iteration has runtime $i\cdot m + m = (i + 1)m$. Therefore, the $n-1$th iteration has runtime $nm$. Summing the runtime of each iteration of the while loop gives us
\[2m + 3m + \dots + nm = m\frac{n(n+1)}{2} - m = \frac{m(n^2 + n) - 2m}{2}\]
This is of $O(mn^2)$

The function takes in an input of two integers ($n, m$) and an array $P$ consisting of the $n$ polynomials of degree $m$. Note that the function assumes that the array is non-empty/$n \neq 0$. The function starts by setting a variable $poly$ to the first element of $P$. It then loops through each element of $P$ and uses $MultiplyPoly$ to update $poly$ to the product of $poly$ and the next element of $P$. The result is the product of all given polynomials. \\

We shall use the fact that the harmonic series is divergent. That is, for all $K \in \mathbb{N}$ there exists some $N \in \mathbb{N}$ such that
   \[\sum_{j = 1}^N \frac{1}{j} > K\]
   Let us define a partition $\mathcal{P}$ where
   \begin{align*}
       t_0 &= 0 \\
       t_j &= \frac{1}{j}, j = 1, 2, \dots, N \\
       t_{N+1} &= 1
   \end{align*}
   The length of $\gamma$ with partition $\mathcal{P}$ is represented by
   \begin{align*}
       \ell (\gamma, \mathcal{P}) &= \sum_{j = 1}^N \lVert \gamma(t_j) - \gamma(t_{j-1}) \rVert \\
       &= \sum_{j = 1}^{N+1} \lVert (t_j, t_j\sin \frac{1}{t_j}) - (t_{j-1}, t_{j-1}\sin \frac{1}{t_{j-1}}) \rVert \\
       &> \sum_{j = 1}^{N+1} \lVert (t_j, t_j\sin \frac{1}{\frac{2}{3\pi}}) - (t_{j-1}, t_{j-1}\sin \frac{1}{\frac{2}{\pi}}) \rVert \\
       &= \sum_{j = 1}^{N+1} \lVert (t_j, t_j\sin \frac{3\pi}{2}) - (t_{j-1}, t_{j-1}\sin \frac{\pi}{2}) \rVert \\
       &= \sum_{j = 1}^{N+1} \lVert (t_j, t_j) - (t_{j-1}, t_{j-1}) \rVert \\
       &= \sum_{j = 1}^{N+1} \sqrt{(t_j - t_{j-1})^2 + (t_j + t_{j-1})^2} \\
       &= \sum_{j = 1}^{N+1} \sqrt{2(t_j)^2 + 2(t_{j-1})^2} \\
       &> \sum_{j = 1}^{N+1} \sqrt{2(t_j)^2} \\
       &> \sum_{j = 1}^{N} t_j = \sum_{j = 1}^N \frac{1}{j} > K\\
   \end{align*}
   Therefore, for any $K \in \mathbb{N}$, we can find a partition $\mathcal{P}$ such that $\ell (\gamma, \mathcal{P}) > K$. Therefore, $\gamma$ has infinite length.

By continuity of $f$, we can find $\delta_3 > 0$ such that $||f(x)|| < \delta_2$ for all $x$, $||x||< \delta_3$. \\
    Pick $\delta = \min\{\delta_1, \delta_3\}$. Then we have

        = & ||D g(f(a+x))Df(a+x) - Dg(f(a+x))Df(a) + \\

    Therefore, for all $\epsilon > 0$ there exists $\delta > 0$ such that for all $x$ such that $||x|| < \delta$ it holds that

and explain why a program-wide constant like keypad does not suffer from the same
drawbacks.
A6. Global variables can be updated anywhere within the file and so multiple functions could be updating the same variable.
This could cause inconsistencies that are difficult to keep track of. The reason why keypad doesn't suffer from this issues
is because (ideally) keypad is never updated. Keypad can be seen as a constant that never changes within the code and so it

As an avid lover of mathematics, I have always been mesmerized by both the beauty of math but also the potential in its applications. Growing up, my father always told me that everything in our universe — whether it be the plants around us or the stars in the sky — could all be described using mathematics. When I was young, I didn't truly comprehend the meaning behind his words, but with the passing of time, I began to dive deeper into the art of problem-solving. Soon, I developed a deepened love and appreciation for perhaps the most simple yet complicated language in the world: the language of mathematics. A short equation, a simple model, from Euler's Formula to the Gold Ratio, mathematics has the power to say so much in so little.

Before applying to Mathcamp, I was unsure whether the experience suited me. However, dabbling in the Mathcamp Quiz problems, I suddenly realized that this was the type of math that I have been searching for. Not memorizing formulas, not bashing through equations, but looking at our world through the lenses of mathematics at its most pure form. Looking past the simple formulas and focusing on their proofs, focusing on why they work. I am unsure as to whether or not I am well prepared for this camp. However, I do know that an opportunity to join Mathcamp will greatly foster my passion for math and open my eyes to what mathematics truly is.

My journey through math started with MathCounts and MathLeague competitions. In 8th grade, I saw a huge gap between my skill level and that of my friends. Watching my peers score higher than me, watching them walk on stage to get the first place medals, I finally decided that it was time for me to put more effort into math. From 8th grade until now, I have been diving deeper and deeper into mathematics and my progress is very evident. I have qualified for states in the High School MathLeague competition for two consecutive years (2020 and 2021). This year, I qualified for AIME with an AMC10A score of 117 (almost a 30 point increase compared to last year).

I first dove into competition math when I was in 7th grade by joining my school math club. We met on a weekly basis to discuss challenging math problems as a group. There, I was introduced to competitions such as MathCounts and MathLeague. I was immediately captivated by the endless possibilities of mathematics and how it was much more than simply applying formulas. The problem solving, the critical thinking, all of it fascinated me. Inspired by my experience in this club, I decided to start something similar — but add my own touch to it. In freshmen year I decided to start my own math club where I taught younger students important math concepts. Every week I would present to a group of students a year younger than me on topics ranging from Geometry to Complex Numbers. I enjoyed going beyond what classroom math could provide for these students. For example, instead of simply handing them the power of a point formulas, I went to the extent of fully proving each of the formulas. Not only did this spark mathematical interest in many of the students, but it also deepened my respect for the art of mathematics.

From there, it is easy to segue into “Nature,” “Community,” “Happiness,” and “Magic” as these sections are about finding true happiness and enjoying childhood. Putting “Nature” and “Happiness” near each other helps juxtapose the two categories. With all magic comes a tint of fear, often in the form of witches, and in Dandelion Wine, the Ravine is a symbol for fear. Fear plays a huge role in the growth of Doug Spaulding which is why “The Ravine” is the perfect introduction to the latter half of the novel: one focused on how Doug has matured and his realization of death. Following “The Ravine” is “The Time Machine,” as this is where Doug is introduced to the concept of death and time. From there, Doug finally realizes that he himself will also die which is why the following section is “The Realization of Death.” Finally, end with the “Memories” section to tie up the whole novel and look back on all of Doug’s adventures.
